WEBVTT

1
00:00:03.600 --> 00:00:11.160
If the strike rates told you how often you win, this table
tells you how often you bleed, and exactly how much. It's
your drawdown map.

2
00:00:11.760 --> 00:00:26.760
It's the MAE Risk Ladder. Remember, MAE is how far a trade
went against you. Each row here is a level of heat, and it
answers three things at once. How many of your trades
pushed beyond that level, how often, and what that
drawdown costs you in real dollars.

3
00:00:27.360 --> 00:00:44.280
Read down the Beyond column. At the top, only ten percent
of your trades ever went beyond a third of a percent
against you. The deep, scary moves are rare. Now drop to
the bottom. By five hundredths of a percent, eighty five
percent of your trades dipped at least that far. A little
heat is almost universal.

4
00:00:44.880 --> 00:01:06.024
Here's how you actually use it. This is the other half of
setting your stop. If you place your stop where eighty
five percent of trades breach it, you'll get tagged out
constantly, even on trades that would have won. Move it
out to a level only ten or twenty percent of trades ever
reach, and you stop bleeding on ordinary noise. The Rate
column is literally the percent of trades a stop there
would have killed.

5
00:01:06.624 --> 00:01:18.000
And the Exposure column turns each level into real money.
The total drawdown that threshold represents at your
current size. It's the cost of choosing a stop too tight,
measured in dollars, not theory.

6
00:01:18.600 --> 00:01:29.160
Pair this with the MFE strike rates, your reward map, and
you see both sides of the trade at once. A stop loose
enough to survive your normal heat, and a target tight
enough to actually get hit.

7
00:01:29.760 --> 00:01:35.016
Set your stop where the ladder says the real moves stop,
not where your fear tells you to put it.
